\begin_body

\begin_layout Title
APPM 2360: Credit Model Project 1
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\align center
Souneth Ly (103036031) (L140) (R241)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\align center
Zhi Huang (102298433) (L150) (R242)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\align center
William Sear (101107069) (L160) (R251)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Abstract
This paper will analyze the behviour of different equations as possible
 models for credit card debt.
 Four different equations will be considered.
 The first two equations will be used to compare the accuracy of a discrete
 time model of debt where intrest is calculated a certain number of time
 each year against a continous model in which the debt is calculated an
 infinite number of times each year.
 These two models will be compared at various intrest rates.
 The final two models are differential equations, one of which defines the
 continous model and one which describes an 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

installment debt
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 model in which an account holder pays a set amount of debt off each year.
 These models will be considered for their properties and how long it will
 take to pay off a set debt.
 Finally an 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

installment savings
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 model will be created based on the reviewed models and then analyzed in
 the context of the observed properties of the previous models under considerati
on.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset CommandInset toc
LatexCommand tableofcontents

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Newpage pagebreak
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Part
Models under Consideration
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Discrete Model for Account Balance
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The first model being reviewed in this paper is a discrete model for a credit
 account balance assuming that the intrest is calculated 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

manually
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 a certain number of times in a time interval (one year in this case).
 The model is the below model 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:model1"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
A_{d}(t)=A_{0}(1+\frac{r}{n})^{nt}\label{eq:model1}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the above model 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:model1"

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{d}(t)$
\end_inset

 is the value of the debt accumulated on the account, 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 is the annual intrest rate (some value such that 
\begin_inset Formula $0\leq r\leq1$
\end_inset

), 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 is the number of times per year that the intrest is applied to the account,
 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 is the time in years since the account was created, and 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{o}$
\end_inset

 is the balance of the account at time 0 (initial balance).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Continous Model for Account Balance
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The second model being reviewed in this paper is a continous model for a
 credit account balance assuming that intrest is calculated an infinite
 number of times in a time interval (one year in this case).
 The model is the below model 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:model2"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
A_{c}(t)=A_{0}e^{rt}\label{eq:model2}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the above model 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:model2"

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{c}(t)$
\end_inset

 is the value of the debt accumulated on the account, 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 is the annual intrest rate (some value such that 
\begin_inset Formula $0\leq r\leq1$
\end_inset

), 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 is the time in years since the account was created, and 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{o}$
\end_inset

 is the balance of the account at time 0 (initial balance).
 The 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 term for the number of times per year that the intrest is applied to the
 account is missing as this model applies intrest an infinite number of
 times every year.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Rate of Change in Account Balance in Continous Model
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The third model being reviewed in this paper is the derivative of model
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:model2"

\end_inset

 which creates the below differential equation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{dA_{c}}{dt}=rA_{c}\label{eq:model3}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the above model 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:model3"

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{c}$
\end_inset

 is the value of the debt accumulated on the account, 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 is the annual intrest rate (some value such that 
\begin_inset Formula $0\leq r\leq1$
\end_inset

), 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 is the time in years since the account was created, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{dA_{c}}{dt}$
\end_inset

 is rate of change of the balance of the account.
 This model will be used to compare model 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:model4"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Installment Debt Rate Model
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The fourth model being reviewed in this paper is an 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

installment debt
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 which calculates the debt accumulated or lost over time assuming that the
 account holder pays a set amount of debt off every year.
 This model is the below model 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:model4"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{dA_{c}}{dt}=rA_{c}-P\label{eq:model4}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the above model 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:model3"

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{c}$
\end_inset

 is the value of the debt accumulated on the account, 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 is the annual intrest rate (some value such that 
\begin_inset Formula $0\leq r\leq1$
\end_inset

), 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 is the time in years since the account was created, 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

 is the amount of debt paid off each year, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{dA_{c}}{dt}$
\end_inset

 is rate of change of the balance of the account.
 This model will be used to compare model 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:model4"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Classification of model 4
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Model 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:model4"

\end_inset

 is a first order equation as the highest derivative is the second derivative,
 but it is not homogenous and there is a 
\begin_inset Formula $-P$
\end_inset

 term that comes from the amount being paid by the account holder each year.
 This model is autonomous as time does not affect the derivative, only the
 y-value has an effect.
 All of the terms in model 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:model4"

\end_inset

 have constant coefficients as 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

 is unchanging and 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 is unchanging.
 Nothing else can be said to classify model 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:model4"

\end_inset

 as it is non-homogenous.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Part
Comparison of Discrete and Continous Account Balance Models
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Comparison of Discrete model as compounding rate increases
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In order to compare model 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:model1"

\end_inset

 to model 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:model2"

\end_inset

 it is useful to consider the behaviour of model 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:model1"

\end_inset

 when 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 (the rate at which intrest is calculated) is increased to infinity such
 that model 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:model1"

\end_inset

 should become model 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:model2"

\end_inset

.
 The below calculations were performed:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $A_{d}(t)=A_{o}(1+\frac{r}{n})^{nt}$
\end_inset

 ts taken to the limit 
\begin_inset Formula $lim_{n\rightarrow\infty}A_{o}(1+\frac{r}{n})^{nt}$
\end_inset

 it becomes 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{o}lim_{n\rightarrow\infty}(1+\frac{r}{n})^{nt}$
\end_inset

 so that we can then define 
\begin_inset Formula $u=\frac{n}{r}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $u\rightarrow\infty$
\end_inset

 so that we can then write 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{o}lim_{u\rightarrow\infty}(1+\frac{1}{u})^{urt}$
\end_inset

 and by definition 
\begin_inset Formula $lim_{u\rightarrow\infty}(1+\frac{1}{u})^{u}=e$
\end_inset

 so the overall equation becomes 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{o}e^{rt}$
\end_inset

 which is model 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:model2"

\end_inset

 as originally expected, thus proving that when 
\begin_inset Formula $n\rightarrow\infty$
\end_inset

 model 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:model1"

\end_inset

 becomes model 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:model2"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Model 1 and 2 Solved for time
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Using algebra with model 1 results in the below equation for t:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
t=ln(\frac{\frac{A}{A_{o}}}{nln(\frac{r}{n}+1)})
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Using algebra with mode 2 results in the below equation for t:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
t=\frac{ln(\frac{A}{A_{o}})}{r}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
These equations can be easily be reproduced by manipulating the model equations
 given in this paper.
 These solutions allow a debtor to calculate how long it will take for their
 debt to become a certain value based on the intrest rate, initial debt,
 and for model 1 the rate at which that debt is calculated.
\end_layout

