\begin_layout Part
Characterization of Installment Debt Model
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Equilibrium Solution
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This paper's examination of model 4 begins by considering its equilibrium
 solution.
 Based on the given model we can conclude that the equilibrium solution
 is 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{p}{r}=A_{c}$
\end_inset

, as this is the only place for which 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{dA_{c}}{dt}$
\end_inset

 is exactly zero for all values of 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

.
 This equilibrium solution is the point at which the account holder has
 enough debt that their rate of monthly payment exactly equals their intrest
 rate.
 This equilibrium solution is unstable as a value either slightly above
 or slightly below this value will result in exponentially increasing debt
 or exponentially decreasing debt respectively.
 As such they will be stuck with a static amount of debt as they will only
 every be paying off the intrest on the account.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Derivative Behavior
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In order to better understand the behavior of model 4 the rate of change
 of the account balance was plotted against the account balance with the
 assumption that the account had an intrest rate of 10% and the account
 holder paid $20 a year against the account.
 The resulting figure 11 is shown below.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\align center
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename Zhi Documents/model4.eps

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Derivative of Model 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:model4"

\end_inset

 at account balance
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig:Derivative-of-Model4"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As we can clearly see in the above figure 11 when the account has a balance
 of $200 the account balance is unchanging in time as the rate of payment
 ($20) is exactly equal to the intrest charged against the account.
 When the account balance is less than $200 the account balance (debt) is
 decreasing (
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{dA_{c}}{dt}<0$
\end_inset

) as the rate of payment is greater than the intrest being charged to the
 account.
 When the account balance is greater than $200 the account balance (debt)
 is increasing(
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{dA_{c}}{dt}>0$
\end_inset

) as the rate of payment is less than the intrest being charged to the account.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Direction Field
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In order to better understand the behavior of model 4 a direction field
 with a few solution curves was plotted under the same initial conditions
 as the plot of the slope in figure 11.
 The below figure 12 captures the resulting direction field.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
placement H
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\align center
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename Zhi Documents/model4dirfield.eps

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Direction Field of Model 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:model4"

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig:Direction-Field-ofmodel4"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In figure 12 above the arrows of the direction field represent the slope
 of the differential equation at that point.
 In this case it shows the rate at which the account holder's balance is
 increasing or decreasing as a result of the intrest charged and the payments
 made.
 When the arrows point downwards they indicate a negative slope, which means
 that solution cuves that move through fields with downwards arrows will
 move towards zero as the debt held by the account holder is decreasing
 until it vanishes.
 When the arrows point upwards they indicate a positive slope, which means
 that solution cuves that move through fields with upwards arrows will move
 towards infinity as the debt held by the account holder is constantly increasin
g.
 The plot exhibits asymptotic behavior when the slope is positive or negative
 as the exponential nature of the solution curves forces the account balance
 to near infinite values in a finite time when the slope is positive and
 forces the account balance to zero quickly when the slope is negative.
 When the account balance is exactly $200 for the conditions described the
 equilibrium conditions are met and the slope is zero for all time.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Initial Value Problem
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The next step in this analysis was to solve the differential equation in
 model 4.
 Using an integrating factor allowed the differential equation to be solved
 which resulted in the below equation where 
\begin_inset Formula $C$
\end_inset

 is some constant:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
A_{c}(t)=\frac{P-Ce^{rt}}{r}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The next step in analyzing this equation is to solve for 
\begin_inset Formula $C$
\end_inset

 which was accomplished by assuming that 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{c}(0)=A_{o}$
\end_inset

 which meant that 
\begin_inset Formula $C=P-A_{o}r$
\end_inset

.
 When substituted back into the found equation the resulting solution to
 the differential equation in mode 4 is:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
A_{c}(t)=\frac{P-(P-A_{o}r)e^{rt}}{r}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This solves model 4 for an initial value of 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{o}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Behaviour of rate of payment over Time
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Time to pay off debt at rate of payment
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In order to better understand how model 4 be analyzed to best determine
 how to pay off debt in the best way.
 In order to best consider the behavior of the time it takes to pay off
 the debt as compared to the amount payed the equation that solves model
 4 was solved for time.
 Simple algera resulted in the below equation:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
t=\frac{ln(\frac{P-rA}{P-rA_{o}})}{r}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It was then assumed that the account holder wanted to maintain a debt of
 $2 dollars on an account that originally had $1 in it and their account
 has an intrest rate of 10%.
 Under these conditions the resulting time values were plotted for differing
 values of payment.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\align center
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename model4timeVp.eps

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Time to pay off debt as a function of paymen
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig:Time-to-pay"

\end_inset

t
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As we can see in the above figure 13 for payments between zero and $1 it
 takes less and less time for the balance to reach the $2 amount.
 Once the rate of payment reaches some value close to $1 the time value
 becomes negative because at that point the rate of payment is larger than
 the rate at which intrest is being added, which means that the only time
 the account could have had a balance of $2 was in the past as the debt
 is decreasing.
 As the payments increase however this low value of the time increases from
 approximatly 1 year in the past as the greater payments mean that the time
 when the account balance was $2 for the initial condition of $1 happened
 closer to the intial condition as the payment is greater and as such a
 smaller amount of time has passed since the point in the past the account
 balance was $2 and the present when the account balance is $1.
 As such we can see when the account balance will reach some point given
 and initial condition, the intrest rate, and then find a workable payment
 so settle the debt to that value in a set amount of time.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Payment needed to pay off debt in a given time
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In order to better understand how model 4 be analyzed to best determine
 how to pay off debt in the best way.
 In order to best consider the behavior of how long it will take to pay
 off the time it takes to pay off the debt as compared to the amount payed
 the equation that solves model 4 was solved for time.
 Simple algera resulted in the below equation:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
P=\frac{-r(A-A_{o}e^{rt})}{e^{rt}}-1
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This formula is useful because it allows the account holder to discover
 how much they will have to pay each period in order to pay off their debt
 in a set time.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It was then assumed that the account holder originally had $1 in their account
 and that account has an intrest rate of 100%.
 Under these conditions the resulting payment values were plotted for differing
 values of time.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
sideways false
status open

