\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Payment to pay off debt as a function of years
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig:Payment-to-pay"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As can be seen in the above figure 14 when the goal is to reach the desired
 payment in a short amount of time (1-3 years) Then the payment slowly increases
 as you need a larger payment to counteract the intrest being generated
 to force the account balance to the desired value.
 However, as the time increases the value of the payment increases towards
 1 because once the payment becomes 1 the intrest rate will exactly cancel
 the payments and the account balance will remain constant.
 As such this plot shows the trends in the payment needed to maintain an
 existing balance with an initial account condition of $1.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Accuracy of Installment Debt Model
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Based on the analysis conducted in the above sections it can be concluded
 that model 4 is a reasonable model for installment debt.
 This is true because model 4 exhibits the behavior we would expect of installme
nt debt as it shows exponential debt increase when payments are less than
 the intrest on the account and exponential debt decrease when payments
 are more than the intrest on the account.
 All other patterns such as the behavior of the solution curve occurs as
 we would expect an installment debt model to work.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
However, this model is severly flawed as it assumes that the account holder
 will not use the credit card.
 This is a severe limitation as most credit card holders will not incur
 an initial value of debt on the card and then not use that card while paying
 a set amount over a long period of time.
 As such this model does not help understand the behavior of the average
 credit card user.
 There is another large limitation of model 4 in that it assumes that the
 account holder will pay a set amount of the debt off every pay period.
 As such this model does not take into account a account holder that changes
 the amount they pay each month.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Part
Installment Savings
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In order to better understand the basic principles of models similar to
 the installment debt model this paper will now consider an installment
 savings model.
 Based on the installment debt model a model for the value of a savings
 account with constant payments being made to it is the below model 5.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{dA_{s}}{dt}=rA_{s}+P\label{eq:model4-1}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the above model 5 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{s}$
\end_inset

 is the balance of the account, 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 is the annual intrest rate (some value such that 
\begin_inset Formula $0\leq r\leq1$
\end_inset

), 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 is the time in years since the account was created, 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

 is the amount deposited in the account each year, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{dA_{s}}{dt}$
\end_inset

 is rate of change of the balance of the account.
 This model exhibits all the behaviors we expect of the installment model
 as it adds the additional deposits to the account balance while also adding
 the intrest generated from the bank.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Initial Value Solution
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The next step in this analysis was to solve the differential equation in
 model 4.
 Using an integrating factor allowed the differential equation to be solved
 which resulted in the below equation where 
\begin_inset Formula $C$
\end_inset

 is some constant:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
A_{s}(t)=\frac{-1(P-Ce^{rt})}{r}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The next step in analyzing this equation is to solve for 
\begin_inset Formula $C$
\end_inset

 which was accomplished by assuming that 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{c}(0)=A_{o}$
\end_inset

 which meant that 
\begin_inset Formula $C=P+A_{o}r$
\end_inset

.
 When substituted back into the found equation the resulting solution to
 the differential equation in mode 5 is:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
A_{c}(t)=\frac{-1(P-(P+A_{o}r)e^{rt})}{r}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Thus this paper can be concluded by presenting this model for savings which
 will exhbit similar behavior to the installment debt model 
\end_layout

